hapter 14 ‘YOU CALL US “GERMANS”, YOU CALL US “BROTHERS” – BUT WE ARE NOT YOUR BROTHERS!’: BRITISH ANTI-NAZI FILMS AND GERMAN-SPEAKING ÉMIGRÉS -- tChapter 15 CARL MAYER: YEARS OF EXILE IN LONDON -- tChapter 16 MUSIC FOR THE PEOPLE: ESCAPISM AND SOCIAL COMMENT IN THE WORK OF HANS MAY AND ERNST MEYER -- tChapter 17 I KNOW WHERE I’M GOING! HEARING GERMANIC MUSIC IN THE SCOTTISH ISLES -- tChapter 18 ‘AN ANIMATED QUEST FOR FREEDOM’: MÁTYÁS SEIBER’S SCORE FOR THE MAGIC CANVAS -- tNOTES ON CONTRIBUTORS -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe legacy of emigrés in the British film industry, from the silent film era until after the Second World War, has been largely neglected in the scholarly literature. Destination London is the first book to redress this imbalance. Focusing on areas such as exile, genre, technological transfer, professional training and education, cross-cultural exchange and representation, it begins by mapping the reasons for this neglect before examining the contributions made to British cinema by emigré directors, actors, screenwriters, cinematographers, set designers, and composers. It goes on to assess the cultural and economic contexts of transnational industry collaborations in the 1920s, artistic cosmopolitanism in the 1930s, and anti-Nazi propaganda in the 1940s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aGermanszGreat Britain. 0aMotion pictureszGreat BritainxHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aBergfelder, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergfelder, Tim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCargnelli, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCargnelli, Christ